Atmospheric neutrinos are a unique tool for studying neutrino oscillations: the oscillated flux contains all flavors of neutrinos and antineutrinos, is very sensitive to matter effects and to both Δm2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\varDelta }m^2_{}$$\end{document} parameters, and covers a wide range of L/E. In principle, all oscillation parameters could be measured, with high complementarity to measurements performed with a neutrino beam. Studying DUNE atmospheric neutrinos is also a promising approach to search for BSM effects such as Lorentz and CPT violation. The DUNE FD, with its large mass and the overburden to protect it from atmospheric muon background, is an ideal tool for these studies.

