				\begin{document}$$K^{+} \rightarrow \mu ^{+} \nu _{\mu }$$\end{document} decay when the proton is mis-reconstructed as a kaon.

The kaon reconstruction is especially challenging for very short tracks, which may traverse only a few wires. The dE/dx signature in signal events can be obscured by additional final-state protons that overlap with the start of the kaon track. Without timing resolution sufficient to resolve the 12 ns kaon lifetime, the dE/dx profile is the only distinguishing feature. The background from atmospheric neutrino events without true final-state kaons, which is important given the presence of FSI, was neglected in previous estimates of p→K+ν¯\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
