The proton decay signal and atmospheric neutrino background events are processed using the same reconstruction chain and subject to the same selection criteria. There are two preselection cuts to remove obvious background. One cut requires at least two tracks, which aims to select events with a kaon plus a kaon decay product (usually a muon). The other cut requires that the longest track be less than 100cm\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${100} \, \text {cm}$$\end{document}; this removes backgrounds from high energy neutrino interactions. After these cuts, 50% of the signal and 17.5% of the background remain in the sample. The signal inefficiency at this stage of selection is due mainly to the kaon tracking efficiency. Optimal lifetime sensitivity is achieved by combining the preselection cuts with a BDT cut that gives a signal efficiency of 0.15 and a background rejection of 0.999997, which corresponds to approximately one background event per Mt·year\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\text {Mt} \, \cdot \, \text {year}$$\end{document}.

The limiting factor in the sensitivity is the kaon tracking efficiency. The reconstruction is not yet optimized, and the kaon tracking efficiency should increase with improvements in the reconstruction algorithms. To understand the potential improvement, a visual scan of simulated decays of kaons into muons was performed. For this sample of events, with kaon momentum in the 150MeV/c\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$150 \, {\text {MeV}}/c$$\end{document} to 450MeV/c\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$450 \, {\text {MeV}}/c$$\end{document} range, scanners achieved greater than 90% efficiency at recognizing the K+→μ+→e+\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$K^{+} \rightarrow \mu ^{+} \rightarrow e^{+}$$\end{document} decay chain. The inefficiency came mostly from short kaon tracks (momentum below 180MeV/c\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$180 \, \text {MeV}/c$$\end{document}) and kaons that decay in flight. Note that the lowest momentum kaons (<150MeV/c\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$< 150 \, \text {MeV}/c$$\end{document}) were not included in the study; the path length for kaons in this range would also be too short to track. Based on this study, the kaon tracking efficiency could be improved to a maximum value of approximately 80% with optimized reconstruction algorithms, where the remaining inefficiency comes from low-energy kaons and kaons that charge exchange, scatter, or decay in flight. Combining this tracking performance improvement with some improvement in the K/p separation performance for short tracks, the overall signal selection efficiency improves from 15% to approximately 30%.

The analysis presented above is inclusive of all possible modes of kaon decay; however, the current version of the BDT preferentially selects kaon decay to muons, which has a branching fraction of roughly 64%. The second most prominent kaon decay is K+→π+π0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$K^{+} \rightarrow \pi ^{+}\pi ^0$$\end{document}, which has a branching fraction of 21%. Preliminary studies that focus on reconstructing a π+π0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\pi ^{+}\pi ^0$$\end{document} pair with the appropriate kinematics indicate that the signal efficiency for kaons that decay via the K+→π+π0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$K^{+} \rightarrow \pi ^{+}\pi ^0$$\end{document} mode is approximately the same as the signal efficiency for kaons that decay via the K+→μ+νμ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
